So possible cases: - 2r^2 = p^13, which is unlikely since 2r^2 would be a prime power. - 2r^2 = p^6 * q, where p and q are primes. Then the number of divisors is (6 + 1)(1 + 1) = 14. Alternatively, 2r^2 = p^12, but that would have 13 divisors, which is odd. Not 14. Alternatively, 2r^2 = p^7, which would have 8 divisors. Not 14. Alternatively, 2r^2 = p^2 * q^1, leading to (2 + 1)(1 + 1) = 6 divisors. Alternatively, 2r^2 = p^3 * q^2, which would have (3 + 1)(2 + 1) = 12 divisors.
